<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/9348257-hedel"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1356937274i/9348257._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/9348257-hedel">Hedel</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">If a grade 4 student is willing to read it, i&apos;d say let them.<br/>It&apos;s hard enough to get kids to read at all. It has some mature themes but I&apos;m sure they&apos;<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">If a grade 4 student is willing to read it, i'd say let them.<br />It's hard enough to get kids to read at all. It has some mature themes but I'm sure they've seen much worse in movies.<br />Since it's your student and not your child, might want to check with what you're allowed to say. I believe some parents are pretty strict on books.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
