<div id="review_1108280387" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1108280387" />
    <a title="Sue" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4481148-sue"><img alt="Sue" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1288460741p2/4481148.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1108280387?book_show_action=true">Nov 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sue" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sue" href="/user/show/4481148-sue">Sue</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780393065787" href="/book/show/875441.Someone_Knows_My_Name">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4481148-sue?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1108280387" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2973567551417275292">An excellent book that shatters my book club&apos;s previous theory that a man cannot write a female character really well. Mr. Hill does a superb job of giving voice to Aminata Diallo, an eleven-year-old girl captured and sold into slavery in the American South. Following her through-out a long lifetime, we see her endure and, eventually, gain her freedom and return to the continent of her birth, only to leave it again by choice. <br/><br/>I learned a good bit about Revolutionary War America from a new perspe</span>
  <span id="freeText2973567551417275292" style="display:none">An excellent book that shatters my book club's previous theory that a man cannot write a female character really well. Mr. Hill does a superb job of giving voice to Aminata Diallo, an eleven-year-old girl captured and sold into slavery in the American South. Following her through-out a long lifetime, we see her endure and, eventually, gain her freedom and return to the continent of her birth, only to leave it again by choice. <br /><br />I learned a good bit about Revolutionary War America from a new perspective. Previous to this book, I had never even heard of the "Black Loyalists," much less what happened to them when the British departed the newly-minted United States. (And since I note that Mr. Hill lives in Ontario, Canada, I wonder if he might be a descendent?)<br /><br />At any rate, I recommend this book to anyone who enjoys well-researched historical fiction. And since this book's Goodreads rating is above 4.0 after more than 33,000 ratings, apparently a lot of other people do, too! </span>
  <a data-text-id="2973567551417275292" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


